                <!-- CONTENT SECTIONS -->
                <h2 id="part1">Part 1: The One-Shot Fallacy</h2>
                <p>The internet is full of "magic prompts" that promise to solve your problems in a single query. "Use this one prompt to write a viral tweet." "This prompt will build your entire business plan."</p>
                <p>It's seductive. It's also fantasy.</p>
                <p>Here's the truth: <strong>AI models are probability machines</strong>. They predict the most likely next token based on patterns in their training data. They don't understand your context, your constraints, or your goals‚Äînot on the first try.</p>
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <h4>üí° Key Insight</h4>
                    <p><strong>The One-Shot Fallacy:</strong> Expecting AI to solve complex problems in a single prompt is like expecting a new hire to nail a project on Day 1 without a briefing. The magic isn't in the prompt‚Äîit's in the <em>process</em>.</p>
                </div>
                <p>When I build a website for a client, I don't expect the first draft to be perfect. I expect it to be a <em>starting point</em>‚Äî30% of the way there. The remaining 70% comes from iteration.</p>

                <h2 id="part2">Part 2: The Iterative Layer</h2>
                <p>The solution isn't "better prompts." The solution is a <strong>structured process</strong> that accounts for AI's limitations and leverages its strengths.</p>
                <p>I call it the <strong>Iterative Layer</strong>‚Äîa four-phase cycle that transforms AI from a coin flip into a reliable collaborator.</p>
                <!-- Hero Image -->
